00:00:27.779 --> 00:00:33.920
Sometimes we call starting a
conversation breaking the ice. You can

00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:40.640
think of the ice as that initial silence
between people. It could be between

00:00:40.640 --> 00:00:48.590
strangers on a plane or co-workers in a
lunchroom and when we break the ice we

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:55.019
say something friendly to start a
conversation. So how do you do that?

00:00:55.019 --> 00:01:04.519
What do you say and what topics our best? Well in our first lesson we had an example of

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:09.230
a greeting between work colleagues who
didn't know each other.

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:13.590
Can you remember how they got their
conversation started after the greeting?

00:01:13.590 --> 00:01:20.170
What did they say? Let's have another
listen to that short dialogue and you

00:01:20.170 --> 00:01:23.450
can listen for the conversation starter.

00:01:23.450 --> 00:01:27.649
A pleasure Shelly quite the setup here
isn't it?

00:01:27.649 --> 00:01:33.070
Yes, they have really gone to town. I
should get them to come decorate my

00:01:33.070 --> 00:01:36.810
house. Yeah right good idea

00:01:37.760 --> 00:01:43.259
So did you hear what the first person said? She said

00:01:43.259 --> 00:01:50.630
quite the setup here isn't it and that
shows us that asking the question is a

00:01:50.630 --> 00:01:55.340
great way to start a conversation
especially if you've just been

00:01:55.340 --> 00:02:02.509
introduced. You can use simple and direct
questions or you can use a comment with

00:02:02.509 --> 00:02:11.060
the tag question. Just a quick note on
vocabulary here. The 'setup' of the room is

00:02:11.060 --> 00:02:14.260
the way it is organized and decorated

00:02:14.520 --> 00:02:21.520
And 'quiet the' means impressive so amber thinks the decoration of the room is very

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:29.980
impressive and Shelly agrees saying
they've really 'gone to town'. If we go to

00:02:29.989 --> 00:02:34.880
town with something it means we make a
big effort.

